Frontier moved to a new communication tool this year based on feedback from so many of you asking if we could just use one app. Bloomz was being used by a number of buildings with great success so we adopted it across the district. Each building has its own code to use if you want to receive posts from a child's school. Anyone can join the FEC using the code listed in this short how to video. Each user has full control of the notifications they receive whether it's via email and/or an app push notification. If you want to receive robocalls for emergency alerts as well, please use the information in this video to add a primary phone number and select robocalls as one of your options.

post_text:
In less than 24 hours, the first cohort of Falcons will enter Frontier buildings for the first time since March. It has been a long road to get here but is finally happening. We know not everything is perfect especially with this first day being so very different than the one we all know. Our task now is to keep doing the best we can each and every day. We need your support to help keep everyone safe. Please check your child(ren)'s temperature before they leave for school. While districts aren't required to have parents report the checks daily, the company that is providing us with the health app is almost ready to push it out to parents. We will get it to parents as soon as it is. In the meantime, conducting a temp check at home, wearing masks, being socially distant, and washing hands are the best ways to prevent the spread of COVID. Thank you all and I can't wait to see our Falcons on their maiden flight back to school!!

Dr. Hughes

post_text: The new turf at the multi-use Laurens Dietz Field attracted a notable alumnus recently! Jake Schum is a former NFL punter who currently plays with the XFL's Tampa Bay Vipers. Everything looks awesome and excited to see some great things happen here."

I will be checking i-Ready and would like to know what your reading, writing, experimenting and making. Submissions that stand out the most will be featured in videos throughout the summer so please include your name, grade and building.

For each submission, you will be entered into a grand prize drawing to take place when we get back to school. The more times you enter the more chances you have to win.

All submissions can be either sent to via email to SuperChallenge@frontiercsd.org or mailed to Superintendent Summer Challenge, 5120 Orchard Ave, Hamburg, NY 14075. We can’t wait to see your ideas!

shared_text:
Western New York United Against Drug and Alcohol Abuse, Inc.
June 26 at 8:00 AM ·

Colleen Duggan, nominated by Beth Anzalone, Executive Director
"We are so pleased to announce Colleen Duggan as a 2020 recipient of the WNY United Friend of Prevention Award! . Colleen is the Assistant Superintendent for Curriculum and Instruction for the Frontier Central School District. Colleen believes that all children can learn. She understands the importance of teaching social emotional skills to increase all students' success. Colleen has been a huge advocate for all of WNY United's services in the 4 elementary buildings as well as programming for Middle School students! She has helped to secure funding to cover the costs of program supplies, knowing that every student deserves the opportunity to learn these important skills. She strives everyday to make sure that the Frontier Community moves forward and stays current in providing programming that increases students ability to navigate the world in which they live. Congratulations Colleen!"
Frontier Central Schools

post_text: What a great day for the Go Baby Go Pit Crew to present Gillie Mae with her custom-engineered PowerWheel! Students from Big Tree Elementary and Frontier High School worked throughout the school year, taking into account the abilities and preferences of Gillie, who has Angelman's syndrome, along with the help of teachers Mrs. Turner and Mrs. Beyette and Fisher Price engineers. From a headrest and side guards to a bubble-making whale, the PowerWheel is 100% Gillie! The pit crew presented the vehicle to Gillie on her birthday Monday along with a crown and made sure to sign the vehicle's hood. #FalconNation #FrontierPride #FrontierFamily

post_text:
Governor Cuomo signed two executive orders today. The first allows mail-in ballot to be received until June 16th while those hand-delivered by 5pm on June 9th. Frontier was on schedule without this delay already having more completed ballots than any other time in the last few decades.

The second order allows traditional in-person graduation for up to 150 people. The 150 would include graduates, family, staff and administrators. If we were to use this option, we would have to break up our graduation into at least 8 groups. Thankfully, Mr, Charland, his assistant principals the Board of Education and I took our time to find a solution that allows all of the Class of 2020 to come together. This order does not affect our planned graduation at the Lancaster Speedway as it falls in the same category as drive-ins. Many more details on exactly how the ceremony will occur will be sent out to the Class of 2020 soon.

Dr. Hughes

On Friday, June 19, the Meals-to-Go program will be closed for a staff day off. We will be doubling up our meals on Thursday, June 18. Meals are distributed weekdays from 9AM-2PM at Blasdell and Cloverbank Elementary and the High School.

The last day of the Meals-to-Go service will be Friday, June 26. We will hold a goodbye cookout that day.

The Summer Meals Program will begin Monday, July 6. Details to come and will be posted on www.frontiercsd.org.

On Friday, June 19, the Meals-to-Go program will be closed for a staff day off. We will be doubling up our meals on Thursday, June 18. Meals are distributed weekdays from 9AM-2PM at Blasdell and Cloverbank Elementary and the High School.

The last day of the Meals-to-Go service will be Friday, June 26. We will hold a goodbye cookout that day.

The Summer Meals Program will begin Monday, July 6. Details to come and will be posted on www.frontiercsd.org.

post_text: The pandemic is changing many things in our daily lives. Due to the reduction in local and state sales tax revenue along with the increase in expenditures to fight the virus, local governments and school districts will likely see a 20% reduction in aid from New York State. Frontier is already the most efficient school district in Erie County because of the low amount of state aid we receive compared to similar schools. A 20% reduction in aid would equal $4.5 million. Erie County sales tax has also decreased significantly which could also impact our district funding, and ultimately instructional programs. The attached letter is one of many being sent to those in the Senate, House of Representatives and White House that have the ability to provide school districts and local governments with the funds to avoid devastating cuts that will harm all students. Please contact your federal representatives to make sure this does not happen.

ConnectLife is feeling thankful.
April 1 at 5:30 PM ·

“We saw the plea for blood donations in the Western New York area, and we wanted to help. What can Frontier High School do to help our community? We decided this was a great way to give back.”

The Frontier Central Schools District has been a great partner of ConnectLife for many years. They run a very successful Donate Life Club and run blood drives throughout the school year.

As a valued partner of ConnectLife, Frontier HS chose to go the extra mile and help the WNY community out in a time of need. It’s partners like this that help to save lives in our WNY community, and for that we are grateful.

Erie County School Nutrition Association
February 21 at 8:00 AM ·

Buffalo Public Schools and Frontier Central Schools were recently awarded Farm to School Grants from NYS Department of Agriculture and Markets! BPS will use their funding to integrate Farm to School programming in the classroom, cafeteria, and community by using a food truck to serve school lunches made with local ingredients to 16 high schools on a rotating basis. The food truck will also support culinary education. 🍅👩‍🌾👩‍🍳🚚

Frontier Central Schools will use their funding to develop a central kitchen to process, freeze, and store local foods. Hamburg Central School District - Hamburg, NY and West Seneca Central School District will also be able to use the processing kitchen.

post_text:
On February 12, twenty students from Frontier and Hamburg High Schools attended the day-long Boys Empowerment day sponsored by The Parent-Child Connection in Hamburg.

The goal of the day was to assist these young men with their development, and use of, traits and characteristics in order to improve their life skills and their academic performance.

Students were challenged to invent a robot that could solve an issue, design and build it. The students invented robots that could bring supplies to patients in hospitals, pick-up dropped items in nursing homes, shovel snow for disabled and elderly neighbors and provide lighthearted entertainment to patients in hospitals, nursing homes or hospice.

Awesome job for all those involved! #FrontierFamily

The team is coached by high school teacher Nicolette Bannister and led by Captains Paige Banach, Kyella O'Connor and Emily Przybysz.

post_text:
Over the weekend, Frontier lost one of its young Falcons. As has been reported by many news outlets, Luca Calanni passed away Saturday after complications from the flu. He was a wonderful young man that positively impacted all those around him. Social workers and counselors will be available at all buildings, with an especially heavy presence at Pinehurst to assist both students and staff.

Our top-notch nursing staff will act as a point of contact for any information parents request regarding the flu including handouts on flu facts. During this extremely difficult time, we ask for privacy for our Falcons and for Luca's family.

post_text: Weather Update...With the lake effect snow band likely to make its way back to the Southtowns and impact dismissal, Frontier CSD schools will be closing all schools an hour early on Wednesday December 11th. The High School will dismiss at 1:05 pm. This will hopefully allow all High School students to get home before the snow band and buses to the Middle School close to an hour early. The bus dismissal timing for Middle School and Elementary School will depend on the snow falling and blowing. The buses could arrive up to an hour early but most likely will be slowed by weather. All afterschool activities are also cancelled.

post_text: Frontier Fly High Volleyball is a before school opportunity for 4th and 5th grade boys at Blasdell Elementary School. It was created and is run by Nick Penberthy, a fifth grade teacher and the Boys Varsity Volleyball Coach. Started last year, the Fly High Volleyball program teaches boys the sport of volleyball by instructing them on a different skill every week culminating in a game which parents can attend in March. The program is free for Blasdell students and has two sessions which meet for 6 weeks each. Through the two years of Fly High Volleyball, 55 boys have participated, including 27 this year. #GoFrontier #FrontierFamily

post_text: During their library period, Mrs. Seifert's class at Blasdell Elementary took part in a STEAM Challenge. Each 4-5 person team was directed to design and build a house given the same materials. The house needed to be able to accommodate at least 2 Pilgrims, withstand rain (5 squirts of water from a sprayer) and extreme wind (hairdryer on low and high settings). The students created a variety of buildings that met all the challenge criteria. #GoFalcons

The Frontier Middle School Drama Club proudly presents the musical “Once On This Island, Jr.” next Thursday, November 21 and Friday, November 22 at 7 p.m. in the Middle School Auditorium.

This musical is an adaption of Hans Christian Anderson’s popular fairy tale, “The Little Mermaid.” It features non-stop song and dance with colorful sets and costumes that will capture the audience's attention.

Frontier’s musical performances never disappoint, so be sure to get your tickets before they sell out! Tickets can be purchased from any cast or crew member for $3 each.

post_text: Blasdell Elementary is piloting a new program for the district called AIM Life (Affirm, Inspire, Motivate). This program was created by Mike Downs, owner of the Defensive Arts Dojo, who is working with our Third Grade students. He and two members of the Defensive Arts Dojo created this program to teach young students to go through life with a positive attitude, have a vision for their future, stay on the "right path", and know their self-worth. The students participate in a variety of activities including a bit of Martial Arts.

The following 7th & 8th grade students from Frontier Middle School were selected for the NYSSMA Area All-State Music Festival which was held November 1-2 at Pioneer Central Schools. Students were selected for honor ensembles based on their solo festival performances in String Orchestra, Full Orchestra, Band, Treble Chorus & Mixed Chorus last spring. Congratulations to all!

Photo row 1 (left to right): Aiden Tardif, Alyson Gleason, Madalyn Shea, Kaylee Hamels, Hailey Korczynski, Jenna Szczepanik, Anthony LaPaglia, Brandon Nowak, Alexander Pfeiffer

post_text: So much great work going on including the start of planning the next capital project. Information and ideas gathered through ThoughtExchange, conversations, the budget vote exit survey, and our admin team are helping to get us started. We will be looking at everything including STEAM, accessible playgrounds, pool renovations, athletic needs and adding better secured entrances to both Pinehurst ES and the Middle School. Tons to do but we hope to get a plan together after further research for a vote next year at this time. Please reach out via phone, email or in person to share any ideas or thoughts with me as Facebook is not the best place to do so. As always #BleedBlue

shared_text:
The Hamburg Sun
September 30, 2019 at 2:58 PM ·

With its N.E.S.T. (Nurturing Every Student's Talents), Frontier Middle School addresses two issues: attendance and mental health. Principal Ryan Sikorski told The Sun they have created a 25-minute block of time every day where they break from academics. Some days, they play recess. On others, students work on character education projects or personal reading. “Academics can be a big stressor for kids,” Sikorski said. “So, we wanted to develop something that would help alleviate that stress and make them want to come to school.”

shared_text:
The Hamburg Sun
October 3, 2019 at 4:17 PM ·

Frontier Central Schools is merging its track team with Lackawanna Schools this spring since Frontier's track-and-field team won't be able to use their regular track at Laurens Dietz Field during the construction of the district's multiuse field project. Lackawanna doesn't currently have a varsity track team. “It’s just both communities working together,” Superintendent Richard Hughes said. “And giving their kids an opportunity. At the same time, I think it gives our kids an opportunity to work with a neighboring school district, get to know other kids outside of their circle.”
(Photo: Harry Scull Jr./Buffalo News)

post_text: Another example of how our Falcons and community make Frontier such a wonderful place to be. #FrontierFamily #FalconNation #BleedBlue
shared_text:
Goin' Bald For Bucks
September 19, 2019 at 7:00 PM ·

And our #1 top fundraising school for 2018-2019 is Frontier Middle School!

This year was Frontier Middle School’s third Bald for Bucks event and second year in a row as our top fundraising school. More than 60 participants raised over $38,000 for Roswell Park.

Frontier’s event is a daylong affair and brings the entire community together. DJ Anthony and players from the Buffalo Bandits also joined in on the fun throughout the day. A shout out goes to Mrs. Klein and her committee for their coordination and organization of this fantastic event.

This past school year has been amazing and we are so grateful for all of our schools participants, stylists and community members who have supported Bald for Bucks! We couldn’t do what we do without you and we can’t wait to kick off the 2019-2020 school year!

post_text:
Two important announcements:

Earlier today we were made aware of a post by a high school student on social media with a picture of bullets. Within minutes of the post and notification by a concerned parent, our principals jumped into action with Town of Hamburg Police Department. An investigation was quickly completed and assessed to NOT be a threat. While specifics about the student and any consequences cannot be shared due to privacy laws, the student involved will be dealt with according to the code of conduct. Thank you to Mr. Charland, Mr. Sikorski and the Town of Hamburg Police for reacting so quickly and professionally.

The second announcement involves a water main break in front of the driveway to Blasdell Elementary this afternoon. Crews are continuing to work this evening and assure us that all will be back to normal before school on Monday.
